    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_969872123" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/969872123" />
    <a title="Abigail Bok" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32345761-abigail-bok"><img alt="Abigail Bok" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442980475p2/32345761.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/969872123?book_show_action=true">Jun 17, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Abigail Bok" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Abigail Bok" href="/user/show/32345761-abigail-bok">Abigail Bok</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer969872123" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5545111476896655364">Rereading this book after decades found me a different reader: some of the pleasures from this beguiling series remain while others have faded to problematic.<br/><br/>Brother Cadfael is a Benedictine monk at an abbey in Shrewsbury, and English town on the border of Wales, in the late Middle Ages (an unknown year some time after the Norman conquest but when Wales was still a cluster of small principalities). Cadfael is himself of Welsh origins, though he knocked about the world quite a bit, including part</span>
  <span id="freeText5545111476896655364" style="display:none">Rereading this book after decades found me a different reader: some of the pleasures from this beguiling series remain while others have faded to problematic.<br /><br />Brother Cadfael is a Benedictine monk at an abbey in Shrewsbury, and English town on the border of Wales, in the late Middle Ages (an unknown year some time after the Norman conquest but when Wales was still a cluster of small principalities). Cadfael is himself of Welsh origins, though he knocked about the world quite a bit, including participating in one of the Crusades, before retiring to the cloister. Although he has a down-to-earth sort of piety and the life suits him pretty well, he retains a relatively secular worldview and regards some of the pious carryings-on of his confreres with skepticism. <br /><br />The target of his skepticism in this instance is a plan by the prior to secure the relics of a saint for the abbey as a means to raising its profile. This plan takes a few of the monks on a quest into Wales to collect the bones of Saint Winifred, whom he believes to be overlooked and uncared-for by the locals. Cadfael accompanies the party as translator.<br /><br />The story settles in once we reach Gwytherin, the site of Winifred's burial, and soon we have a murder for Cadfael to investigate. The village, and Welsh medieval society in general, are painted in rosy hues, with fair (but sexy) maidens and stalwart lads and men of the soil with deep common-sense. It is a picture that, on this reading, both seduced me and made me a bit squeamish. The vision of a harmonious, edenic Britain where everyone knows her place and is happy to stay in it is simultaneously appealing and problematic--but that's my own reading issue, and let's get on with Brother Cadfael.<br /><br />The murder is suitably baffling, and the author introduces no anachronistic elements as Cadfael begins to investigate, no "if only we had some means of reading the whorls on a person's fingers as a means to identification" jarring bits. Cadfael applies ordinary logic and intelligence, combined with a shrewd sense of human nature, to reach his conclusions. There are red herrings and complications enough to keep the reader happy, and he need feel no regrets when the perpetrator is ultimately revealed--even if the details of the resolution may be ethically questionable.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5545111476896655364" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


